title: For Sale:  Sig p226 MK25
postcontent: I have for sale a Sig MK25 that was manufactured in 2012. It has some holster wear but is in excellent mechanical condition. This particular sig (as compared to the p229 that I owned) has an excellent trigger. The 229 I owned had quite a bit of "overtravel" or "trigger slap" in the double action mode, which could cause some loss of fine accuracy. This one breaks right as the trigger reaches the frame and has no discernible overtravel to it. It is also smoother than my 229 was. It shoots to the sights and has all the pluses that come with the MK25 such as phosphate coated internals, hard chromed barrel etc. I have tried my best to capture the worst of the wear areas in the pictures.  I have upgraded it with an E2 grip kit which makes it feel much better in the hand in my opinion. There are some areas on the grip's checkering that have been flattened somewhat. The original grips are also included and the 3 original 15 round phosphate coated magazines. Buyer must be a Montana resident, and must be willing to show valid state issued ID and fill out a bill of sale at the time of purchase. Thanks for looking and feel free to ask any questions you might have.

title: For Sale:  Colt Trooper MK 1 .357 Revolver
location: west suburbs of chicago, Chicago, Illinois
postcontent:
This was the first firearm I ever owned.  I've always had a soft spot for revolvers, but as I'm more interested in getting into rifles I'm looking to replace my Trooper with an AR-15.

I purchased this Trooper on consignment from my local gun store.  As I never met the previous owner, this is only speculation, but due to the holster wear (purely cosmetic, and in my opinion it gives this gun the flavor a gun of it's age deserves) the previous owner was a police officer.

Everything on this gun works perfectly, and I'm much more accurate with it than I am on any striker fired or 1911 style pistol.

The grips of the gun are in like with, and thus I assume to be, original grips.

The trigger though is what I feel is the best piece of this gun.  The Trooper is a single/double action pistol.  The double action isn't anything that makes me stop and say wow, however the single action makes me wish I could magically pull it out and use it in every other gun that I have ever shot.

If you have any questions at all about this firearm, don't hesitate to let me know.  I'm happy to clarify anything, and supply more detailed/specific pictures upon request.

title: For Sale/Trade:  New model CZ P-07 9mm front cocking serrations and three dot photo luminous sights x 15 round mags
postcontent:
The CZ P-07 is the updated version of the CZ 75 P-07 Duty. The debut of the full-size P-09 last year brought refined lines and interchangeable backstraps to our polymer Omega line. This year the compact-sized P-07 follows suit, with new features and a nitrated slide finish that wears longer and has increased corrosion resistance. The pistol as a whole has been dehorned, removing any sharp edges to make it more comfortable for all-day carry.

Like the P-09, the P-07’s safety and decocker are interchangeable with a few minutes and minimal tools. Add to that small, medium and large backstraps and an integrated 1913 Picatinny rail on the dust cover and the P-07 is adaptable to the shooter and their needs, from service pistol to bedside protector to the envy of the shooting range.

The P-07 shares the P-09’s updated trigger shape which is more comfortable for long days at the range, as well as its snag-free hammer and forward cocking serrations. Metal 3-dot sights and a beefed up magazine spring round out the bevy of updates, resulting in the best P-07 we’ve had to date.

title: For Sale:  M14 EBR trigger shoe
postcontent:
Once you try one, you'll wonder how you ever managed without one.

What do you get for your money?
One M14 EBR trigger shoe, Two set screws, One .050 Allen wrench.
Each M14 EBR trigger shoe has a hard Salt bath Nitride finish.

 Why should you install the M14 EBR trigger shoe?
The M14/M1A trigger is designed to be pulled in more of an upward direction.
 The original trigger design is not user friendly when a pistol grip is used.
The M14 EBR trigger shoe is wider & longer, with more surface area.
The steel M14 EBR trigger shoe is designed with the correct angle
 required to direct the trigger pull more to the back than up.
The tip of the trigger can no longer stab the tip of your trigger finger.
The trigger pull feels natural & lighter with the M14 EBR shoe installed.

Shipping is included CONUS.
